    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-04-03T15:45:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-04-03T15:45:00-05:00" n="631"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d631">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">715.1715/313: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-04-03T15:00:00-05:45"
                            >April 3, 1929—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 8:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>84. President Moncada has furnished me with a copy of the following telegram,
                    dated April 2nd, which he sent to the President of Honduras: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I beg of you to take into consideration the costs to both countries of
                            the troops stationed on the border. The sooner we terminate this <pb
                                facs="0675" n="557" xml:id="pg_557"/> abnormal situation the less
                            danger there will be for us in the interior and the exterior.<note n="7"
                                xml:id="d631fn7">See <ref target="frus1929v01#pg_976">vol. <hi
                                        rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 976</ref> ff.</note> Partial
                            compliants [<hi rend="italic">compliance?</hi>] injure only us, I beg of
                            you to cooperate in the peace of both republics. I shall always be the
                            best friend of Honduras. If our constitutions prevent the crossing of
                            frontiers and if for this reason we are unable to end the disaster, God
                            save both countries. Hatred of the Americans blinds many, eventually
                            that hatred might well carry us to disaster.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated to Tegucigalpa.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Eberhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
